[[et:Animalist]]

'''Animalier school''' or animalier<ref name=Kjellberg>{{cite book|last1=Kjellberg|first1=Pierre|title=Bronzes of the 19th Century|date=1994|publisher=Schiffer Publishing, Ltd.|location=Atglen, Pennsylvania|isbn=0-88740-629-7}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Animalier|website=wiktionary.org|url=https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/animalier|accessdate=October 29, 2016}}</ref><ref name=Payne>{{cite book|last1=Payne|first1=Christopher|title=Animals in Bronze -- Reference and Price Guide|date=1986|publisher=Antique Collectors' Club Ltd.|location=Woodbridge, Suffolk, England|isbn=0-90746-245-6}}</ref> movement was a roughly late 18th century to late 19th century movement and [[Art movement|school of art]], which took as its subject in various [[Figurative art|figurative]] forms the animal kingdom or [[Animal|Kingdom Animalia]]. The movement predominantly centered around Paris, France, and Italy, with some offshoots in England, Germany, and North America. [[File:Whistlejacket by George Stubbs edit.jpg|thumb|''Whistlejacket'' by George Stubbs]] [[Image:Rosa Bonheur with Bull , by E L Dubufe.jpg|thumb|left|[[Edouard Louis Dubufe]], ''Portrait of Rosa Bonheur'' (1857). Symbolic of her work as an ''Animalière,'' the artist is depicted with a bull.]] Some examples of animalier artists and their subjects are [[George Stubbs]] and [[Jules Moigniez]] (paintings and sculpture of horses), [[Antoine Barye|Antoine-Louis Barye]] (sculpture of bulls and humans), and [[Rembrandt Bugatti]] (felines, human figures, and zoo animals).
== History == [[File:Theseus Slaying Minotaur by Barye.jpg|thumb|left|''Theseus Slaying Minotaur'' by Barye]] Animals as a [[Motif (visual arts)|visual motif]] were used in [[ancient art]] and in [[tribal art]], in [[animal style]] art and objects but were not generally represented as figurative, anatomically correct, creatures.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Janson|first1=H.W.|title=History of art : a survey of the major visual arts from the dawn of history to the present day|date=1986|publisher=H.N. Abrams|location=New York|isbn=0-8109-1094-2|pages=81–82|edition=3rd }}</ref> The [[Celts|Celtic]]-[[Germanic culture|Germanic]] animal style with its "combination of abstract and organic shapes, of formal discipline and imaginative freedom, became an important element ... in the art of the [[Dark Ages (historiography)|Dark Ages]]."<ref>{{cite book|last1=Janson|first1=H.W.|last2=Janson|first2=Anthony F.|title=History of art : a survey of the major visual arts from the dawn of history to the present day|date=1986|publisher=H.N. Abrams|location=New York|isbn=0-8109-1094-2|pages=255–256|edition=3rd }}</ref> During the [[Baroque]] period in France and England, a 1670 commissioned [[terracotta]] model for a sculpture of [[Louis XIV]] titled ''Equestrian Statue of Louis XIV'' by [[Gian Lorenzo Bernini]] was rejected on the grounds that it was not suitable to the dignity of the king.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Janson|first1=H.W.|title=History of art: a survey of the major visual arts from the dawn of history to the present day|date=1986|publisher=H.N. Abrams|location=New York|isbn=0-8109-1094-2|pages=553–554|edition=3rd}}</ref>
The term animalier was first used by the French press and [[Salon (Paris)|salon]] jurors, often as a derogatory term.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gallery|first1=The Bronze|title=Les Animaliers - The 19th century French movement of Bronze Sculpture|url=http://bronze-gallery.com/info/info.cfm?infoID=9|website=bronze-gallery.com|accessdate=21 October 2016}}</ref> The Paris salon thought animal subjects too common for fine art, but with the opening of the new [[Jardin des Plantes|Paris Jardin des Plantes]] zoo and the [[Ménagerie du Jardin des plantes]], interest in animal art increased.<ref>http://www.iub.edu/~iuam/online_modules/metz/collection.html</ref> The Dukes of [[Duke of Orléans|Orleans]], [[Duke of Luynes|Luynes]], [[Duke of Montpensier|Montpensier]], and [[Duke of Nemours|Nemours]] were soon to become Barye's patrons. In 1882 [[Edouard Manet]] created a portrait in pastel on canvas of the animalier artist Julien de La Rochenoire, which has been owned by the [[Getty Museum]] since 2014.<ref>http://www.getty.edu/art/collection/objects/265936/edouard-manet-portrait-of-julien-de-la-rochenoire-french-1882/</ref>[[File:George Stubbs - Zebra - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|George Stubbs - Zebra - Google Art Project]] The art of George Stubbs became a favorite of collector [[Paul Mellon]], who donated many of Stubbs' paintings to the [[Yale Center for British Art]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Maj|first1=Yale Center for British Art, Lec|title=Zebra|url=http://collections.britishart.yale.edu/vufind/Record/1669240|website=collections.britishart.yale.edu|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>
It has been observed that "many animal sculptures were modeled in plaster for exhibition and cast later in bronze editions. The size and variety of an edition depended on the popularity of the piece at exhibition, and many Barye, Mêne, and Fratin pieces were so popular that they were cast in very large editions."<ref>{{cite web|title=The Metz Collection|url=http://www.iub.edu/~iuam/online_modules/metz/collection.html|website=www.iub.edu|accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref> {{multiple image | align=right | direction=horizontal | width= | footer= | width1=180 | image1=Édouard Manet - Le peintre animalier La Rochenoire.jpg | alt1= | caption1=Édouard Manet – ''Le peintre animalier'' La Rochenoire | width2=228 | image2=Alfred Dedreux - Une Amazone Au Bois De Boulogne.jpg | alt2= | caption2=Alfred Dedreux – Une Amazone Au Bois De Boulogne }}
== Animalier artists == [[File:Rembrandt bugatti zoo antwerpen 1910.jpg|thumb|left|Rembrandt Bugatti at the zoo in Antwerp, Belgium]]Artists of the animalier movement were referred to as ''[[les animaliers]]''. Important artists of the animalier movement included [[Antoine-Louis Barye]] (1796–1875), [[Rembrandt Bugatti]] (1884–1916), [[George Stubbs]] (1724–1806), [[Alfred Dedreux]] (1810–1860), [[Christopher Fratin]] (1801–1864),<ref>http://www.bronze-gallery.com/sculptors/artist.cfm?sculptorID=21 </ref><ref>http://www.worldcat.org/title/concise-history-of-bronzes/oclc/15625 </ref> Alexandre Guionnet, [[Pierre-Jules Mêne]] (1810–1879).<ref>http://www.artic.edu/aic/collections/artwork/artist/Mene%2C+Pierre-Jules </ref> [[Rosa Bonheur]] (1822–1899), [[Isidore Bonheur]] (1827–1901), [[Anna Hyatt Huntington]] (1876–1973), [[Paul-Edouard Delabrierre]] (1829–1912), [[Alfred Dubucand]] (1828–1894), [[Jules Moigniez]] (1835–1894) and [[Émile-Coriolan Guillemin]] (1841–1907).
== Animalier reproductions == Many beautiful [[replicas]] are made of animalier sculpture, which may be cast or molded in any size and of any material. The most desirable of these are exact in detail and made from the same material, such as [[cast iron]], [[spelter]], or [[cast bronze]], as used in the artist's original sculpture. Most of the original animalier sculptors used the traditional [[lost wax]] process of casting prevalent at the time. Alexandre Guionnet<ref>{{cite web|title=Auguste Cain. Expert art authentication, certificates of authenticity and expert art appraisals - Art Experts|url=https://www.artexpertswebsite.com/pages/artists/cain.php|website=www.artexpertswebsite.com|accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref> was exceptional in that he worked in wood. Modern reproductions of the original sculptures frequently use [[patinated]] [[verdigris]] cast bronze or iron, or [[Resin casting|bonded marble resin]] (pulverized reconstituted marble combined with resin glue), as well as various other materials and techniques, such as a composite of [[Capiz]] [[placuna placenta]] oyster shells, also known as window oyster shells, which come primarily from the [[Philippines]] (where they are known as ''kapiz'').{{clear}}
