{{lang|de|'''Ordnung muss sein'''}} is a [[German language|German]] proverbial expression which translates as "there must be order." The idea of "order" is generally recognized as a key cliche for describing [[Culture of Germany|German culture]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Tomalin|first=Barry|title=Germany - Culture Smart!: The Essential Guide to Customs & Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=neGgAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Ordnung+muss+sein%22&dq=%22Ordnung+muss+sein%22&hl=en&ei=E67fTrauLZSutwfOxbjMBQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CEQQ6AEwBA|year=2006|publisher=Kuperard|isbn=978-1-85733-306-0|page=37}}</ref> [[Franz von Papen]], for instance, cited it in 1932 as [[Frederick the Great]]'s "classic expression".<ref>{{cite book|last=Dodd|first=William J.|title=Jedes Wort wandelt die Welt: Dolf Sternbergers politische Sprachkritik|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J0_PqTRgZOoC&pg=PA143|year=2007|publisher=Wallstein|isbn=978-3-8353-0230-3|page=143|language=German}}</ref> As a slogan used by [[Paul von Hindenburg]], it became "world famous" in 1930, according to ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1930/11/09/archives/german-pilots-course-is-a-long-hard-grind-work-at-transport-school.html|title=GERMAN PILOTS COURSE IS A LONG, HARD GRIND; Work at Transport School From Which von Gronan Flew Is Arduous--25 in 1,000 Applicants Get In|last=Graudenz|first=John|date=9 November 1930|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=7 December 2011}}</ref> A longer version is contained in a mid-19th century collection of proverbs where the title is a [[Wellerism]]: {{lang|de|Ordnung muss sein, sagte Hans, da brachten sie ihn in das Spinnhaus}} (in English: "Order must be, said Hans, as they took him to the madhouse)."<ref name=simrock>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cAs-AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA361|title=Die deutschen Sprichwörter|last=Simrock|first=Karl|author-link=Karl Joseph Simrock|year=1846|location=Frankfurt am Main|page=361|language=German}}</ref>

Related German proverbs are {{lang|de|Ordnung ist das halbe Leben}},<ref name=simrock/> literally "order is half of life", humorously extended in the [[Anti-proverb|antiproverb]] {{lang|de|und Unordnung die andere Hälfte}} ("and disorder the other half"). Similarly, a proverb says {{lang|de|Wer Ordnung hält, ist nur zu faul zum Suchen}} meaning "he who keeps order is just too lazy to spend his time searching".{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}

There is an {{lang|de|[[Municipal police (Germany)|Ordnungsamt]]}} (Public Office for Order, [[Code enforcement]]) in every German municipality and city. Minor or petty offenses are called {{lang|de|Ordnungswidrigkeit}} (meaning "offense, (or rather) contrarity to (public) order" or indeed the American (among others) similar concept of disorderly conduct).

