[[Image:sculpture-garden.jpg|right|thumb|The Esplanade Ernest-Cormier, a sculpture garden in Montreal, Quebec, Canada, with [[Melvin Charney]]'s work ''Colonnes allégoriques''.]]A '''sculpture garden''' or '''sculpture park''' is an outdoor garden dedicated to the presentation of [[sculpture]], usually several permanently sited works in durable materials in [[landscaping|landscaped]] surroundings.<ref>{{cite book|author1=McCarthy, Jane |author2=Laurily Keir Epstein  |last-author-amp=yes |title=A Guide to the Sculpture Parks and Gardens of America|publisher=Michael Kesend|location=New York|year= 1996 |page=1|isbn=978-0-935576-51-1}}</ref> These installations are related to several similar concepts, most notably [[land art]], where landscapes become the basis of a site-specific sculpture, and [[topiary]] gardens, which consists of training live plants into living sculptures.

A sculpture garden may be private, owned by a museum and accessible freely or for a fee, or public and accessible to all. Some cities own large numbers of [[public art|public sculptures]], some of which they may present together in city [[park]]s.

Exhibits range from individual, traditional sculptures to large [[site-specific art|site-specific]] [[installation art|installations]]. Sculpture gardens may also vary greatly in size and scope, either featuring the collected works of multiple artists, or the artwork of a single individual.

== History ==
Sculpture gardens have a long history around the world - the oldest known collection of human constructions is a [[Neanderthal]] "sculpture garden" unearthed in Bruniquel Cave in France in 1990.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jaubert|first=Jacques|last2=Verheyden|first2=Sophie|last3=Genty|first3=Dominique|last4=Soulier|first4=Michel|last5=Cheng|first5=Hai|last6=Blamart|first6=Dominique|last7=Burlet|first7=Christian|last8=Camus|first8=Hubert|last9=Delaby|first9=Serge|date=2016-06-02|title=Early Neanderthal constructions deep in Bruniquel Cave in southwestern France|url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v534/n7605/full/nature18291.html|journal=Nature|language=en|volume=534|issue=7605|pages=111–114|doi=10.1038/nature18291|issn=0028-0836}}</ref> Within the cave, broken stalagmites were arranged in a series of stacked or ring-like structures approximately 175,000 years ago.

In the United States, the oldest public sculpture garden is a part of the joint park and wildlife preserve [[Brookgreen Gardens]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sciway.net/sc-photos/georgetown-county/brookgreen-gardens.html|title=Brookgreen Gardens - Murrells Inlet South Carolina SC|website=www.sciway.net|access-date=2016-12-16}}</ref> located in South Carolina. The property was opened in 1932, and has since been included on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nationalregisterofhistoricplaces.com/sc/georgetown/state.html|title=National Register of Historical Places - SOUTH CAROLINA (SC), Georgetown County|website=www.nationalregisterofhistoricplaces.com|access-date=2016-12-16}}</ref>

